### 1. One-Line Summary
* Rozena is the easier, flatter, more forgiving “controlled attack” rubber, while Rakza 7 Soft is the spinnier, higher-arc, softer-feeling option with more dwell and better opening-loop help.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Rozena feels a bit cleaner and more direct on light contact, so simple drives, punches, and compact counters come out with less trampoline. Rakza 7 Soft has more soft-sponge rebound and a bouncier feel at gentle impact.
    * **Top End:** They are close in raw speed on official ratings (Rozena 83, Rakza 7 Soft 84), but Rakza 7 Soft reaches its best pace more through elastic catapult, while Rozena feels more measured and easier to keep on line under pressure.
    * **Linearity:** Rozena is the more linear rubber overall. Rakza 7 Soft has a more noticeable soft-tensor kick as you engage the sponge.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Rakza 7 Soft has the clearer edge. Its softer ~40° sponge, higher throw, and longer dwell make it easier to lift backspin and create quality on the first topspin.
    * **Max Spin:** Rakza 7 Soft is stronger here on paper and in design intent, with official spin rated 88 versus Rozena’s 70.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Rakza 7 Soft is built around a grippy topsheet with high natural rubber content, so it bites the ball more aggressively. Rozena still spins well, but its identity is more forgiveness than maximum grab.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Rakza 7 Soft throws higher. Yasaka explicitly positions it as a high-arc rubber, and Butterfly lists Rozena’s arc at 75, which is moderate rather than very high.
    * **Safety:** Rakza 7 Soft gives more net clearance on loops; Rozena gives a flatter, more direct trajectory that many players find easier for punchy close-table offense.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Rozena feels more crisp-stable; Rakza 7 Soft feels softer, more cushioned, and more elastic on contact.
    * **Dwell:** Rakza 7 Soft has more dwell by design because of the softer sponge. Rozena’s 35 hardness is also not hard, but its playing character is still more compact and less “holding” than Rakza 7 Soft.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Rozena is usually easier for players who want the rubber to ignore small angle mistakes; Butterfly explicitly markets its tolerance and forgiveness. Rakza 7 Soft is controlled, but the softer, grippier nature makes it a bit more reactive.
    * **Touch Play:** Rakza 7 Soft offers better spin manipulation and touch variation, especially on short receives and loaded pushes. Rozena is calmer and simpler for basic placement and keeping the ball low without over-activating the sponge.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Rozena is the safer passive blocker because it is flatter and less springy on small inputs.
    * **Active Counter:** Rakza 7 Soft is better when you actively brush and counter-spin, especially on backhand topspin exchanges. Rozena is better when your counter is more compact, direct, and placement-based.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose Rozena if:**
    * you want the more forgiving rubber overall;
    * you value stability, flatter trajectory, and easier passive blocking;
    * you play a controlled attack game close to the table and do not want excessive bounce;
    * you are developing technique and want a rubber that covers small contact errors well.

* **Choose Rakza 7 Soft if:**
    * you want more spin, more arc, and more dwell;
    * you rely on opening loops, spinny backhand play, and heavy serve/receive quality;
    * you prefer a softer, more cushioned impact with stronger grip on the ball;
    * you are comfortable managing a slightly more dynamic short game in exchange for more rotation and looping safety.
